#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:16
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptography"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "In general everyday usage, Cryptography is the act or art of writing in secret characters. In technical jargon it may be defined as the science of using mathematics to encrypt and decrypt data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:20
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptanalysis"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptanalysis is the study of how to compromise (defeat) cryptographic mechanisms. It is the science of cracking code, decoding secrets, violating authentication schemes, and in general, breaking cryptographic protocols.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:24
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptology"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:27
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptology is the discipline of cryptography and cryptanalysis combined. Cryptology is the branch of mathematics that studies the mathematical foundations of cryptographic methods.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "Encryption"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "Encryption is the transformation of data into a form that is as close to impossible as possible to read without the appropriate knowledge (e.g. a key). Its purpose is to ensure privacy by keeping information hidden from anyone for whom it is not intended.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:32
#, no-wrap
msgid "Decryption"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "Decryption is the reverse of encryption; it is the transformation of encrypted data back into an intelligible form.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:36
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cipher"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "A method of encryption and decryption is called a cipher.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "Hash Functions (Digest algorithms)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptographic hash functions are used in various contexts, for example to compute the message digest when making a digital signature. A hash function compresses the bits of a message to a fixed-size hash value in a way that distributes the possible messages evenly among the possible hash values. A cryptographic hash function does this in a way that makes it extremely difficult to come up with a message that would hash to a particular hash value. Some examples of the best known and most widely used hash functions are described below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "**a)** - **SHA-1 (Secure Hash Algorithm)** -This is a cryptographic hash algorithm published by the United States Government. It produces a 160 bit hash value from an arbitrary length string. It is considered to be very good.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "**b)**- **MD5 (Message Digest Algorithm 5)** - is a cryptographic hash algorithm developed at RSA Laboratories. It can be used to hash an arbitrary length byte string into a 128 bit value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "Algorithm"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "It describes a step-by-step problem-solving procedure, especially an established, recursive computational procedure for solving a problem in a finite number of steps. Technically, an algorithm must reach a result after a finite number of steps. The efficiency of an algorithm can be measured as the number of elementary steps it takes to solve the problem. There are two classes of key-based algorithms. They are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "**a) **-- **Symmetric Encryption Algorithms ( secret-key)**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "Symmetric algorithms use the same key for encryption and decryption (or the decryption key is easily derived from the encryption key). Secret key algorithms use the same key for both encryption and decryption (or one is easily derivable from the other). This is the more straightforward approach to data encryption, it is mathematically less complicated than public-key cryptography. Symmetric algorithms can be divided into stream ciphers and block ciphers. Stream ciphers can encrypt a single bit of plaintext at a time, whereas block ciphers take a number of bits (typically 64 bits in modern ciphers), and encrypt them as a single unit. Symmetric algorithms are much faster to execute on a computer than asymmetric ones.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:57
#, no-wrap
msgid "Examples of symmetric algorithms are: AES, 3DES, Blowfish, CAST5, IDEA and Twofish.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:59
#, no-wrap
msgid "**b) -- Asymmetric algorithms (Public-key algorithms)**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "Asymmetric algorithms on the other hand use a different key for encryption and decryption, and the decryption key cannot be derived from the encryption key. Asymmetric ciphers permit the encryption key to be public, allowing anyone to encrypt with the key, whereas only the proper recipient (who knows the decryption key) can decrypt the message. The encryption key is also called the public key and the decryption key the private key or secret key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "RSA is probably the best known asymmetric encryption algorithm.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "Digital Signature"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "A digital signature binds a document to the owner of a particular key. Digital signatures are used to verify that a message really comes from the claimed sender.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "The digital signature of a document is a piece of information based on both the document and the signer's private key. It is typically created through the use of a hash function and a private signing function (encrypting with the signer's private key). A digital signature is a small amount of data that was created using some secret key, and there is a public key that can be used to verify that the signature was really generated using the corresponding private key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "Several methods for making and verifying digital signatures are freely available but the most widely known algorithm is the RSA public-key algorithm.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptographic Protocols"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:75
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cryptography works on many levels. On one level you have algorithms, such as block ciphers and public key cryptosystems. Building upon these you obtain protocols, and building upon protocols you find applications (or other protocols). Below is a list of common everyday applications that make use of cryptographic protocols. These protocols are built on lower level cryptographic algorithms.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "i.) Domain Name Server Security (DNSSEC)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is a protocol for secure distributed name services. It is currently available as an Internet Draft.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:81
#, no-wrap
msgid "ii.) Secure Socket Layer (SSL)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "SSL is one of the two protocols used for secure WWW connections (the other is SHTTP). WWW security has become important as, increasing amounts of sensitive information, such as credit card numbers, are being transmitted over the Internet.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:85
#, no-wrap
msgid "iii.) Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol (SHTTP)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:87
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is another protocol for providing more security for WWW transactions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "iv) E-Mail security and related services\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "**GnuPG** - The GNU Privacy Guard - is compliant with the proposed OpenPGP Internet standard as described in RFC2440.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "v) SSH2 Protocol\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "This protocol is versatile for the needs of the internet, and is currently used in the SSH2 software. The protocol is used to secure terminal sessions and TCP connections.\n"
msgstr ""

