#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:284
#, no-wrap
msgid "<span id=\"anchor-2\"></span>Revocation certificates\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:286
#, no-wrap
msgid "Revocation certificates are used revoking keys in case someone gets knowledge of your secret key or incase you forget your passphrase. They are also useful for other various functions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:288
#, no-wrap
msgid "To create a revocation certificate\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:290
#, no-wrap
msgid "While still logged in as the user ying. Create a revocation certificate. It will be displayed on your\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:292
#, no-wrap
msgid " standard output. Type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:294
#, no-wrap
msgid "[ying@serverXY ying\\]$*** gpg --gen-revoke ying@serverXY***\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:296
#, no-wrap
msgid "Follow the prompts and enter your passphrase when prompted to do so.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:298
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now create a revocation certificate that will be stored in an ASCII format in a file called -\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:300
#, no-wrap
msgid " “revoke.asc”. Type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:302
#, no-wrap
msgid "[ying@serverXY ying\\]$*** gpg --output revoke.asc --gen-revoke ying@serverXY***\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:304
#, no-wrap
msgid "You should store the revocation certificate in a safe place and even make a hard printed copy.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:306
#, no-wrap
msgid "Exporting Public Keys\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:308
#, no-wrap
msgid "The whole point of all this encrypting, signing and decrypting business is because people wish to communicate with one another - but they also wish to do so in as secure a manner as possible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:310
#, no-wrap
msgid "With that said - the perhaps not to so obvious has to be stated:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:312
#, no-wrap
msgid "To communicate with other people using a public-key based cryptosystem - you must exchange public keys.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:314
#, no-wrap
msgid "Or at least make your public key available in any publicly accessible place (Bill-boards, web pages, key servers, radio, T.V, SPAMMING via e-mail ..etc ….. )\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:316
#, no-wrap
msgid "To export your public keys\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:318
#, no-wrap
msgid "Export your public key in binary format to a file called “ying-pub.gpg”. Type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:320
#, no-wrap
msgid "[ying@serverXY ying\\]$ ***gpg --output ying-pub.gpg --export &lt;your\\_key’s\\_user\\_ID&gt;***\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:324
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Please replace &lt;your\\_key’s\\_user\\_ID&gt; with any string that correctly identifies your keys. On our sample system this value can be any one of the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:326
#, no-wrap
msgid "    ying@serverXY, ying, yang\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:328
#, no-wrap
msgid "    OR\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:330
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The actual key ID - 1D12E484\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:332
#, no-wrap
msgid "Export your public key to a file called “ying-pub.asc”. But this time generate it in\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:334
#, no-wrap
msgid " ASCII-armored format. Type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:336
#, no-wrap
msgid "[ying@serverXY ying\\]$***gpg --output ying-pub.asc --armor --export ying@serverXY ***\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:338
#, no-wrap
msgid "Use the cat command to view the binary version of ying’s public key (ying-pub.gpg)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:340
#, no-wrap
msgid "  (To reset your terminal type: “reset”)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5. '
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:342
#, no-wrap
msgid "Use the cat command to view the ASCII version of ying’s public key (ying-pub.asc)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '6. '
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:344
#, no-wrap
msgid "You will observe that the ASCII version is more suited for posting on web-pages or spamming etc..\n"
msgstr ""

