#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:558
#, no-wrap
msgid "OpenSSH is OpenBSD's SSH (Secure SHell) protocol implementation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:560
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is a FREE version of the SSH protocol suite of network connectivity tools. OpenSSH encrypts all traffic (including passwords) to effectively eliminate eavesdropping, connection hijacking, and other network-level attacks. Additionally, OpenSSH provides a plethora of secure tunneling capabilities, as well as a variety of authentication methods.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:562
#, no-wrap
msgid "It helps to provide secure encrypted communications between two untrusted hosts over an insecure network (such as the internet).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:564
#, no-wrap
msgid "It includes both the server side components and the client side suite of programs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:566
#, no-wrap
msgid "**sshd**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:568
#, no-wrap
msgid "The server side includes the secure shell daemon (sshd). sshd is the daemon that listens for connections from clients.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:570
#, no-wrap
msgid "It forks a new daemon for each incoming connection. The forked daemons handle key exchange, encryption,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:572
#, no-wrap
msgid "authentication, command execution, and data exchange. According to sshd’s man page, sshd works as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:574
#, no-wrap
msgid "For SSH protocol version 2…..\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:576
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each host has a host-specific key (RSA or DSA) used to identify the host. When the daemon starts, it does not generate a server key (As is the case in SSH protocol version 1). Forward security is provided through a Diffie-Hellman key agreement. This key agreement results in a shared session key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:578
#, no-wrap
msgid "The rest of the session is encrypted using a symmetric cipher, currently 128 bit AES, Blowfish, 3DES, CAST128, Arcfour, 192 bit AES, or 256 bit AES. The client selects the encryption algorithm to use from those offered by the server. Additionally, session integrity is provided through a cryptographic message authentication code (hmac-sha1 or hmac-md5).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:580
#, no-wrap
msgid "Protocol version 2 provides a public key based user (PubkeyAuthentication) or client host (HostbasedAuthentication) authentication method, conventional password authentication and challenge response based methods.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/labs/security/lab9-cryptography.md:582
#, no-wrap
msgid "The SSH2 protocol implemented in OpenSSH is standardized by the “IETF secsh” working group\n"
msgstr ""

